   {:e #blake3 "eeac1602ae449e5b20e2ca23715dd820254845385f48bd22959f2110dbfc425a" :a :task/description :v "Option F Hybrid WAL architecture: separate VISIBILITY (in-memory Store), DURABILITY (WAL append+fsync), and GIT-READINESS (.edn file generation) into three independent concerns, each optimized independently. Motivated by FrankenSQLite WAL patterns + asupersync structured concurrency + the insight that braid's grow-only set model is SIMPLER than a database (no MVCC, no page locking, no GC needed — set insertion commutes). COMPONENTS: (1) WAL format + writer (append-only binary with CRC + hash chain). (2) Group commit thread (channel-based write batching, single fsync per batch — O(1) fsyncs regardless of agent count). (3) PASSIVE checkpoint (background WAL→edn conversion, non-blocking). (4) RwLock<Store> multi-threaded dispatch (unlimited read concurrency, microsecond write critical section). (5) Crash recovery (checkpoint + WAL replay + edn regeneration). PERFORMANCE TARGET: 50 agents at 1 write/s with <5ms write latency and <100ms read latency. DEPENDS-ON: DAEMON-WRITE epic (DW0-DW4 provide CLI→daemon routing that this epic's daemon internals serve). AXIOLOGICAL ALIGNMENT: C1 (WAL is append-only, .edn immutable), C2 (.edn filenames remain BLAKE3), C4 (.edn files remain the CRDT merge unit — WAL is local/ephemeral), Git (edn = git source of truth, WAL never enters git)." :op :assert}
